[PER Dewhurst] wants to bill feds for undocumented prisoners 
[LOC AUSTIN] , [LOC Texas] -- Days after calling for the impeachment of President [PER Barack Obama] , Lt. Gov. [PER David Dewhurst] is demanding that the president pay for the 130,000 undocumented immigrants who are housed in county jails across [LOC Texas] -- a tab that could run nearly $157 million in the past two years alone . 
In a letter to [LOC Obama] , [PER Dewhurst] said the federal government should reimburse [LOC Texas] counties for the cost of housing the undocumented immigrants because the feds have failed to secure the [LOC U.S.] [LOC Mexico] border as they should have . 
" [MISC It’s] time we ask for that money back , " [PER Dewhurst] said in an email to supporters this week , asking them to sign a petition supporting his position . 
" It’s outrageous that county jails pay for housing to more than 130,000 people that illegally enter our state . 
" In my experience , I believe the immigration conversation begins and ends with strict border security , as our counties can no longer fund this massive financial burden . " 
In his letter to [LOC Obama] , [LOC Dewhurst] wrote: " The dollars expended in this fashion would be better spent enhancing law enforcement efforts to better protect our citizens . " 
No word yet from [LOC Washington] on what they think of Dewhurst’s demand , but don’t expect a check to be arriving anytime soon . 
[PER Dewhurst] , who has drawn three [MISC GOP] challengers in his re-election bid , has made a sharp turn to the right in his political rhetoric since losing a [LOC U.S.] [ORG Senate] runoff to tea party star [PER Ted Cruz] in July 2012 . 
People seeking bargains lined up at a state-run food store in [LOC La Paz] on Thursday . 
Two weeks ago , [PER Dewhurst] publicly advocated [MISC Obama’s] impeachment at a tea party forum in [LOC Fort Worth] -- a move that drew surprise since it came from [ORG Texas’ No.] 2 officeholder . 
State and county officials have complained for years that detained immigrants are costing local taxpayers , and federal officials have declined to reimburse any costs because the jailed suspects are being held on local charges . 
Similarly , state officials have also complained that state prisons are holding thousands of undocumented immigrants who were convicted of state crimes . 
At one point last year , well over 12,000 state convicts had deportation detainers on them -- meaning that as soon as they complete their sentence or are paroled they are subject to being deported , officials said . 
Most are [MISC Mexican] citizens , prison officials said . 
Proposals to deport convicts serving time for nonviolent crimes before they were paroled have failed to gain support from legislative leaders , who feared if they were paroled and returned home they would simply slip back across the border into [LOC Texas] . 
The savings from that plan were estimated to be at least $15 million , officials said at the time . 
