UPDATING AN EMAIL LAW FROM THE PAST CENTURY 
[PER Steven Warshak] , a [LOC Cincinnati] businessman who built an empire selling male sexual enhancement drugs , was convicted of wire fraud several years ago , based in large part on his email correspondence , which authorities had extracted via a subpoena under a 1986 law governing electronic privacy . 
A federal appeals court in [LOC Ohio] later found , however , that the government had violated Warshak’s constitutional right to privacy . 
The court said investigators should have convinced a judge that there was probable cause and obtained a search warrant , as though his messages had been stashed in a desk drawer . 
Although the court let the conviction stand , the case highlighted the conflicting legal rules that govern electronic privacy . 
[ORG Congress] is now set to clarify those rules , bringing that quarter-century-old law , the [ORG Electronic Communications Privacy Act] , or [ORG ECPA] , in line with the [MISC Internet] age . 
On Thursday , the [ORG Senate Judiciary Committee] will start deliberating a measure that would require the government to get a search warrant , issued by a judge , to gain access to personal emails and all other electronic content held by a third-party service provider . 
The current statute requires a warrant for emails that are less than 6 months old , but it lets the authorities gain access to older communications – or bizarrely , emails that have already been opened – with just a subpoena and no judicial review . 
The law governs the privacy of practically everything entrusted to the [MISC Internet] – family photos stored with a Web service , journal entries kept online , company documents uploaded to the cloud , and the flurry of emails exchanged every day . 
The problem is that it was written when the cloud was just a cumulus in the sky . 
[LOC Silicon Valley] companies as well as advocacy groups from the political left and right have been lobbying for change for many years , and reform legislation seems to be gaining broad political support . 
Even the [ORG Justice Department] appears to have approved one major change: requiring law enforcement to get a search warrant for all kinds of electronic content , no matter how long it has been in electronic storage or what exactly electronic storage means . 
“Changing the law has become more of an imperative because of the growth of cloud computing , because everyone including members of [ORG Congress] are storing sensitive info with third-party providers and they want it to be protected , ” said [PER Greg Nojeim] , senior counsel at the [MISC Washington-based] [ORG Center for Democracy and Technology] , which is financed partly by [LOC Silicon Valley] companies and which is part of a coalition pushing for reform . 
“The technology is advancing and people realize the law has to keep pace.” 
Updating the bill could have a broader impact on civil cases as well , clarifying who can gain access to emails , photos and [ORG Facebook] posts in corporate litigation and divorce court . 
It could also lay out clearer rules for government agencies like the [ORG Internal Revenue Service] to follow to gain access to private citizens’ emails . 
The agency told [ORG Congress] recently that it seeks search warrants before reading taxpayer emails , though its written policy says otherwise , according to an information request filed by the [ORG American Civil Liberties Union] . 
Courts across the country , apparently baffled by how to apply the existing law , which applies to content held in “electronic storage , ” have ruled in sometimes contradictory ways over the privacy of electronic material in both civil and criminal cases . 
In one prominent case , [PER Lee Jennings] sued a relative of his wife who broke into his [ORG Yahoo] account and ferreted out emails describing an extramarital affair that were later used as incriminating evidence in divorce proceedings . 
[PER Jennings] claimed a violation of his privacy under the electronic privacy act , but the highest court in his home state of [LOC South Carolina] held that his emails , which sat on Yahoo’s servers , were not held in “electronic storage” and therefore were not covered by the statute . 
A federal court in [LOC California] years earlier had ruled differently in another case , interpreting “electronic storage” far more broadly . 
Jennings’ lawyer , [PER Neal K. Katyal] , a former acting solicitor general in the [LOC Obama] administration , asked the [ORG Supreme Court] to reconcile the dueling interpretations . 
The court declined to hear the case this month , effectively leaving it to [ORG Congress] to clarify the law . 
Although the appeals court ruling in the [LOC Warshak] criminal case is binding only in the 6th Circuit , it has since become the default legal threshold for many Web companies . 
[ORG Facebook] says it turns over content created by users – pictures , posts , messages – only after it is served with a search warrant , though a subpoena suffices for basic subscriber information , including a user’s name and email address . 
Twitter , too , says “requests for contents of communication require a [LOC U.S.] search warrant , ” and it informs users when it receives a request for information from a government agency . 
[ORG Microsoft] , which operates email and cloud storage services , follows a similar practice , insisting on a search warrant for “content , ” including documents , photos , email and instant messages . 
With a subpoena , the company can divulge a user’s [ORG Internet Protocol] record , though , which can be used to establish a person’s location . 
“The law is so old it doesn’t account for how we have turned into a digital society , ” said [PER Bryan Schilling] , a lawyer at [ORG Microsoft] . 
He offered an offline analogy: “If somebody had a storage unit , law enforcement would be required to get a search warrant , ” he said . 
“It’s the same thing now , as we store more and more of our content in the cloud , consumer or enterprise.” 
The original sponsor of the 1986 law , Sen. [PER Patrick Leahy] , [ORG D-Vt.] , has called its overhaul his top priority for the year . 
He and Sen. [PER Mike Lee] , [PER R-Utah] , have introduced a measure requiring law enforcement to obtain a warrant for all electronic content , including emails , regardless of how old they are . 
That overhaul is backed by an unlikely coalition . 
Amazon and [ORG Google] , which offer cloud-based services to consumers and businesses , are lobbying for the change , along with startups like [ORG Evernote] and [ORG Tumblr] , which operate modern-day private diaries . 
They have joined with advocacy groups as diverse as the [ORG American Civil Liberties Union] and [ORG Americans for Tax Reform] . 
The issue of email privacy received the greatest attention last year , when Gen. [PER David H. Petraeus] , the former director of the [ORG Central Intelligence Agency] , resigned after an inquiry into his email correspondence turned up evidence of an extramarital affair . 
He and his biographer , [PER Paula Broadwell] , had exchanged amorous correspondence in a “draft” folder of a shared [MISC Gmail] account , apparently to elude detection . 
Those draft messages , because they had not been transmitted across the [MISC Internet] , could have been viewed by federal authorities with nothing more than a subpoena , according to current law . 
[PER GEORGE JONES] IN REAL LIFE AND REAL TIME 
Early in 1977 , a couple of years after he and [PER Tammy Wynette] had divorced , the country music star [PER George Jones] played a show at the [LOC Stardust Inn] in [LOC Waldorf] , [LOC Md.] , his first in the [LOC Washington] area in several years . 
I was then a young pop music critic at [ORG The Washington Post] , so it fell to me to write a profile of the notoriously hard-drinking singer . 
What followed was an experience so intense , so remarkable for its raw emotional force , that I could not help but think of it Friday , when it was announced that [PER Jones] had died in a [LOC Nashville] , [LOC Tenn.] , hospital at the age of 81 . 
That weekend I learned two important things about Jones: that there was very little distance between him and his songs , and that the same qualities that made him a great artist also made his life a torment . 
In those days he was still unashamedly carrying a torch for [PER Wynette] , who had left him because , as she put it in legal papers she filed , he “drinks to such an extent that he becomes completely and absolutely unmanageable.” 
On stage that weekend , he reworked songs like “She Thinks I Still Care” and “Picture Me Without [MISC You”] so that they included references to her , making them almost embarrassingly personal , as if she were in the audience and he was singing only to her . 
But it was on his tour bus between sets that I saw [PER George Jones] more achingly and nakedly vulnerable than any performer I have ever encountered , before or since that night . 
He was dressed in a flashy leisure suit and wore a pair of glittering diamond rings on his left hand , including one with his initials , but as he talked about [PER Wynette] and how much he still loved her , he began to weep . 
I don’t think he was drunk . 
He talked about how he was trying to stay dry for [PER Tammy] , who by that time had already re-married and divorced again . 
Within a year or two , he would develop a cocaine habit that would send his career off the rails , but there was no sign of that either . 
This was just [PER George Jones] in real life and real time . 
It is hard today , in a time when irony has become a dominant cultural mode and artists are screened from reporters by phalanxes of handlers , to imagine so public a breakdown happening or a celebrity letting his pain be so visible . 
But [LOC Jones] wasn’t ashamed or embarrassed by that display , and when he went back to the stage for a second set of what he described to me as “sad , sloppy tear-jerkers , ” his singing was even more passionate and inspired , with his twangy , somewhat nasal voice cracking in all the right places with what had to be genuine feeling , not artifice . 
Over a career that lasted nearly 60 years , [PER Jones] recorded more than 100 albums , and over and over again , he didn’t just sing the songs that were given to him . 
In the best of his recordings , as on that night , he also inhabited them , so that anyone listening to him could be sure: He really means it , he has really lived this song about heartbreak or hangovers and knows what it means , poor soul . 
As someone who grew up in [LOC Chicago] listening mostly to the blues , I had no special fondness for country music , whose only local outlet in those days was the radio station [ORG WJJD] . 
But seeing [PER George Jones] live for the first time that cold night in southern [LOC Maryland] was a revelation , because in his own highly idiosyncratic way he showed himself to be no less soulful a singer than [PER Howlin’ Wolf] on something like “How Many More Years” or [PER Otis Redding] on “I’ve [MISC Been Loving You Too] [MISC Long.”] 
Despite all the drinking and drug binges that would dog his career , [PER Jones] never lost that gift . 
In 2009 , assigned to write a profile of the [MISC Canadian] singer-songwriter [PER Leonard Cohen] for this newspaper , I walked into [LOC Cohen’s] [LOC New York] hotel suite to find him playing one of [MISC Jones’] late-career gems , “Choices , ” on his iPod . 
[PER Cohen] expressed great admiration for [PER Jones] and then recited one of the song’s most powerful verses: 
I was tempted 
By an early age I found 
I liked drinkin’ 
Oh , and I never turned it down 
There were loved ones 
But I turned them all away 
Now I’m living and dying 
With the choices I made 
@In part because of his consistent “nipping , ” as he called it , [PER Jones] never enjoyed the crossover success of his contemporaries [PER Johnny Cash] and [PER Merle Haggard] , and so his passing will probably not have the broad cultural resonance that Cash’s did . 
But he was , hands down , a superior singer , a fact obvious to everyone in the country music field: As [PER Waylon Jennings] once sang , “If we all could sound like we wanted to , we’d all sound like [PER George Jones.”] 
But even within the confines of “pure country , ” whatever that term might mean today , [PER Jones] did not stand still . 
He began his career very much in the mold of his idol [PER Hank Williams] , singing tunes about honky-tonks and carousing . 
He never lost his affection for that genre , but over the years he also evolved into a master of ballad singing , especially on his duets with [PER Melba Montgomery] and [PER Wynette] , both before and after they were married . 
And though a brief late ‘50s flirtation with rockabilly didn’t pan out , [PER Jones] also knew how to rock . 
It’s almost forgotten now , but he and [PER Elvis Presley] once were co-headliners on a [LOC Louisiana] [MISC Hayride] tour , and generations of rock 'n’ roll bands , including ones I played in , have covered songs like “Why Baby Why , ” “White Lightning” and “The Race Is On” and found them to be guaranteed crowd-pleasers . 
Beginning in the 1980s , [PER Jones] , with the help of his fourth wife , [PER Nancy Sepulvedo] , pulled himself out of his tailspin . 
But by then the country music mainstream had begun to move on to more polished styles , and [PER Jones’] visceral approach fell out of fashion . 
In recent years , [PER Jones] had thought of himself as a relic , and expressed bitterness at what he saw as the disregard for what he represented . 
All that may be true , but it can’t – and doesn’t – dim the magnificence of his achievements , any more than his personal weaknesses and demons did . 
[ORG DEATH ROW] INMATE ’ S REQUEST FOR DNA TESTING IS REJECTED 
The state of [LOC Mississippi] rejected on Monday a request to submit physical evidence for DNA testing made by a prisoner scheduled to be put to death Tuesday evening . 
[PER Willie J. Manning] , convicted in 1994 of murdering two college students , had been repeatedly rebuffed in the courts as he sought to have DNA tests performed on certain crime scene evidence . 
But the most recent requests came about because of two letters sent by the [ORG Justice Department] in recent days to the prosecutor who handled [MISC Manning’s] trial . 
The letters concerned the trial testimony of an [ORG FBI] expert asked to examine “hair fragments” found at the scene of the murders . 
The expert testified that in this case he could determine only that the hairs came from an [MISC African-American] but that hair comparison analysis was capable , given better samples , of matching a hair to a particular individual . 
[PER Manning] is black ; the murder victims were white . 
The prosecutor cited this testimony several times in his closing arguments . 
In a letter dated May 2 , the [ORG Justice Department] said the expert’s testimony about the general capability of hair analysis – that it could match a hair to a specific individual – was erroneous and “exceeded the limits of the science.” 
Then , in a letter dated May 4 , the department further said that such analysis could not “determine” that a hair came from a person of a certain race , as the expert testified at one point , only that the hair “possesses certain traits that are associated with a particular racial group.” 
The [ORG FBI] offered in both letters to perform DNA testing on the hair fragments . 
Manning’s lawyers argued that these letters constituted new evidence and thus that the hairs , as well as other evidence collected at the scene including a rape kit and fingernail scrapings , should be submitted for [MISC DNA] testing before [PER Manning] is put to death . 
In the response denying the requests , the state attorney general , [PER Jim Hood] , called the new requests a “red herring , ” saying that the letters did not “represent new evidence , ” nor did they repudiate the testimony given by the [ORG FBI] expert in 1994 . 
Manning’s lawyers are still lobbying the governor for a stay of execution . 
On Friday , Manning’s brother and the [ORG Mississippi Innocence Project] filed suit to preserve all the physical evidence for DNA testing even if the execution is carried out . 
FOCUS TURNS TO THREE SUSPECTS IN [MISC BELGIAN] DIAMOND ROBBERY 
[LOC PARIS] – Investigators in three countries continued unraveling the plot behind a brazen $50 million diamond robbery in [LOC Belgium] , focusing Thursday on a [MISC Swiss] lawyer , a real estate businessman and a [MISC French] luxury car exporter with a prison record for fraud . 
After a series of raids Tuesday and Wednesday in [LOC Switzerland] , [LOC Belgium] and [LOC France] , the authorities started releasing some of the more than 30 men who were arrested and questioned in connection with the Feb. 18 robbery , in which armed men in police suits attacked a [MISC Zurich-bound] plane minutes before takeoff from the [LOC Brussels] airport . 
Investigators in [LOC Belgium] and [LOC Switzerland] suspect that a critical organizer in the plot was [PER Marc Bertoldi] , 43 , a [MISC French] car exporter whose listed address was in a wealthy seaside neighborhood of [LOC Antibes] on the [PER Cote] d’Azur and who owns a restaurant in [LOC Casablanca] , [LOC Morocco] . 
He was arrested Tuesday in [LOC France] and remains in prison , awaiting a hearing May 16 in [LOC Metz] for extradition to [LOC Belgium] . 
Investigators said Bertoldi’s arrival in [LOC Geneva] after the theft had provided a critical breakthrough in the inquiry . 
After Bertoldi’s arrest , the police trailed an unidentified [MISC Swiss] lawyer and a real estate owner Wednesday as they made an exchange of a key to a cellar where some of the stolen diamonds were discovered . 
Bertoldi’s lawyer , [PER Olivier Rondu] , said Thursday that his client denied the accusations against him and was willing to be extradited to [LOC Belgium] to confront the charges . 
“He has a surprising position that he wants to go to [LOC Belgium] as quickly as possible to explain himself , because he says he has done nothing , ” [PER Rondu] said . 
“He denies participating in the robbery at [LOC Brussels] airport.” 
[PER Rondu] also confirmed that his client had been convicted in the past for fraud and robbery and had served a prison term . 
In [LOC Switzerland] , where eight people were arrested Wednesday , the real estate owner and the [MISC Swiss] lawyer remained in detention . 
[PER Francois Canonica] , a lawyer for the [MISC Swiss] lawyer , also denied any wrongdoing on his client’s part , telling a [MISC Swiss] newspaper , [LOC Tribune de Geneve] , “My client has faith that ultimately he will be acquitted.” 
MILITANT SAYS HE IS BEHIND FATAL [LOC NIGER] ATTACK 
[LOC DAKAR] , [LOC Senegal] - [PER Mokhtar Belmokhtar] , the mastermind of the January seizure of an [MISC Algerian] gas plant that left dozens of foreign hostages dead , has claimed responsibility for another terrorist attack - the suicide bombings on Thursday in [LOC Niger] that killed about 30 people , including 24 soldiers and at least six jihadists . 
If true , Belmokhtar’s claim would put one of the [MISC Sahel’s] most hardened militants , whom [MISC Chad’s] military said in March it had killed in battle , back at the center of the region’s fight against [MISC Islamist] jihad . 
Experts saw no reason to doubt Belmokhtar’s claim , despite the unconfirmed claim by the [MISC Chadian] military , which said that [ORG Belmokhtar] had died in the [LOC Ifoghas] mountain range during the joint [MISC French-Chadian] campaign against [MISC Islamist] militants in northern [LOC Mali] . 
Neither [LOC France] nor [LOC Algeria] , where [PER Belmokhtar] has been a wanted man for years for his role in the 1990s civil war there , ever confirmed Chad’s assertion . 
No proof was presented of his death , and a fellow militant later denied it in an [MISC Internet] posting . 
The latest claim by Belmokhtar - a veteran of training by al-Qaida in [LOC Afghanistan] , years of terrorist acts against the [MISC Algerians] and multiple kidnappings of [MISC Westerners] in the [LOC Sahara] - came hours after bomb-laden vehicles ripped through a military installation and a [MISC French-owned] uranium mine in [LOC Niger] . 
[PER Belmokhtar] , who is considered perhaps the most redoubtable of the region’s surviving militants , also played a leading role in the [MISC Islamist] takeover of northern [LOC Mali] last year . 
The new claim was made on a number of different websites . 
In one , [PER Belmokhtar] himself , using his nom de guerre [PER Khalid Abu al-Abbas] , signed a claim on jihadist forums that fighters from his “Those Who Sign with [MISC Blood”] brigade - the same group that carried out the [LOC Algeria] attack - blew up the [MISC French] mine and the [LOC Niger] base , according to the [ORG SITE Monitoring Service] , which tracks extremists . 
The claim was posted by the same user who put out a video of [MISC Belmokhtar] in December , SITE said , and it asserted that the attacks were in retaliation for purported assertions by [LOC Niger] to have defeated the jihadists . 
“We warn all the countries that are intending to participate in the [MISC Crusader] campaign on our land , even if in the name of peacekeeping , that we will make you taste the heat of death and wounds in your homelands and among your soldiers , ” SITE quoted [PER Belmokhtar] as saying . 
[LOC BRITAIN] AND [LOC ECUADOR] MAY DISCUSS ASSANGE CASE 
[LOC LONDON] - The [MISC Ecuadorean] foreign minister is due to travel to [LOC London] this month and has offered to meet his [MISC British] counterpart to discuss the impasse over the [PER Julian Assange] case , officials from both countries said on Monday . 
Assange , the founder of the anti-secrecy group [ORG WikiLeaks] , has been holed up for nearly a year in the tiny [MISC Ecuadorean] Embassy here , stymying [MISC British] attempts to extradite him to [LOC Sweden] . 
The [MISC Swedish] authorities want to question Assange in connection with accusations that he sexually assaulted two women , but he has said he fears that the [MISC Swedes] will in turn send him to the [LOC United States] to answer questions about his role in helping disseminate classified government information via WikiLeaks . 
The development concerning [ORG Assange] came on the same day as the court-martial of [MISC Pfc.] [PER Bradley Manning] , the Army private accused of passing on sensitive diplomatic and military information , was scheduled to begin in [LOC Maryland] . 
[PER Manning] has pleaded guilty to 20 of the 22 charges against him , but he has not admitted to the most serious charge , aiding the enemy . 
[PER Manning] has said he gave the material to [PER WikiLeaks] , which then helped disseminate it . 
Assange has never acknowledged that [PER Manning] was his source . 
A spokesman for the [MISC Ecuadorean] government said last week that the foreign minister , [PER Ricardo Patino] , planned to travel to [LOC London] on June 16 , three days before Assange’s first anniversary in the embassy , and to meet with [PER Assange] . 
[ORG “The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Ecuador] has informed [LOC U.K.] authorities that Mr. [PER Patino] will be in [LOC London] and has offered to meet with Foreign Secretary [PER William Hague] to discuss the case of [PER Julian Assange] , ” the spokesman said . 
A spokesman for the [MISC British] [ORG Foreign Office] said it was informed of [ORG Patino’s] trip on Friday and was “considering” his request for a meeting with [ORG Hague] . 
“U.K. government officials have been in regular contact with representatives of the [MISC Ecuadorean] government , both in [LOC London] and [LOC Quito] , about Mr. [PER Assange] , ” the [ORG Foreign Office] said in a statement . 
“We hope the visit will contribute to our joint commitment to finding a diplomatic solution to this issue.” 
Last week , [ORG Reuters] quoted [PER Patino] as saying his government was preparing a document in which it would argue that [LOC Britain] is legally obliged to give Assange permission to travel to [LOC South America] . 
SOUTH AFRICAN LEADER CITES 'PROGRESS' IN MANDELA'S CONDITION 
[LOC JOHANNESBURG] - After four days in the hospital battling a lung infection , former President [PER Nelson Mandela] of [LOC South Africa] “is responding better to treatment , ” President [PER Jacob Zuma] told [ORG Parliament] in [LOC Cape Town] on Wednesday . 
“We are very happy with the progress that he’s now making , following a difficult few days , ” [PER Zuma] said . 
It was the first report of an improvement in Mandela’s condition since he was admitted to a hospital in [LOC Pretoria] early Saturday after suffering a recurrence of a persistent lung ailment , a legacy of the tuberculosis he contracted during the 27 years he was imprisoned for opposing apartheid . 
His health has been frail lately , and this hospitalization was his fourth in the last seven months . 
Government officials in the last few days had been more downbeat , describing [MISC Mandela’s] condition as “serious but stable” with no improvement . 
[PER Mandela] , 94 , is being treated in an intensive care unit , where close family members have been visiting him regularly . 
Among them are his daughters , his former wife [PER Winnie Madikizela-Mandela] and his grandson [PER Mandla Mandela] . 
His current wife , [PER Graça Machel] , canceled a speech in [LOC London] to be by his side . 
[PER Mandla Mandela] , who is a traditional leader in the [LOC Eastern Cape] village where his grandfather was born , spoke to reporters outside [MISC Mandela’s] home . 
“My grandfather is the father of the nation , ” he said . 
“He’s embraced by the global community , and we appreciate the support that we’ve received.” 
As an underground leader of the banned [ORG African National Congress] , [PER Mandela] was convicted of treason 49 years ago Wednesday . 
He was sentenced to life in prison , but was released in 1990 as the government , under intense international pressure , began negotiating with [PER Mandela] and the [ORG ANC] . 
[PER Mandela] was elected as [MISC South Africa’s] first black president in 1994 and served one term . 
He retired from public life in 2004 , and has not been seen in public since 2010 , when [LOC South Africa] hosted the [MISC World Cup] . 
MILITANTS ATTACK U.N . 
COMPOUND IN [LOC SOMALIA] 
[LOC MOGADISHU] , [LOC Somalia] - Militants staged a deadly assault on a [ORG U.N.] compound here Wednesday , the latest in a series of attacks that have chipped away at the security gains the [MISC Somali] capital has experienced in recent years . 
The [MISC Shabab] , the fearsome [MISC Islamist] militant group that once controlled much of the capital , claimed responsibility for the attack , which government officials said left at least 15 people dead , including seven attackers . 
The assault began when [MISC Shabab] militants blew up a pickup truck rigged with explosives outside the compound , witnesses said . 
Militants armed with rifles and wearing explosive vests then stormed the facility on foot . 
[MISC Somali] and [ORG African Union] troops responded to the scene . 
The ensuing firefight lasted more than an hour , punctuated by a series of blasts . 
Somalia’s minister of interior and national security , [PER Abdikarim Hussein Guled] , told reporters that the dead included four foreigners , four [MISC Somalis] working for the [ORG United Nations] as security personnel , as well as the attackers . 
In a statement , [MISC Somalia’s] prime minister , [PER Abdi Farah Shirdon Saaid] , condemned “the senseless and despicable attack on innocent [ORG U.N.] civilians.” 
[LOC Mogadishu] has experienced a period of relative calm since [ORG African Union] forces and the [MISC Somali] army pushed back the [MISC Shabab] , leading it to announce a hasty retreat from the city in 2011 . 
The militant group vowed to shift tactics more toward guerrilla assaults , assassinations and suicide bombings . 
Militants “are now in complete control of the entire compound and the battle is still ongoing , ” the [PER Shabab] said on its Twitter feed during the attack . 
“Inside the compound are several clueless foreigners who were lulled into a false sense of security by a strong disinformation campaign ! ” 
The [PER Shabab] , who have sworn allegiance to al-Qaida , said that the group’s [ORG Martyrdom Brigade] had carried out the attack . 
The [ORG U.N.] compound sits on a busy stretch of road near the airport . 
An ambulance worker , [PER Abdirisak Moumin] , said that he had collected 13 wounded civilians , six of whom died from their injuries . 
[PER Nicholas Kay] , the [ORG U.N.] special representative for [LOC Somalia] , was outside the compound at a meeting nearby when the attack occurred . 
He called the attack an act of terrorism intended to derail Somalia’s drive toward recovery after decades of war and instability . 
While the [ORG United Nations] would review its security procedures , “the [ORG U.N.] is committed to its mission , ” [PER Kay] said in a telephone interview . 
“We’re here to help and we’re here to stay.” 
VIGIL FOR MANDELA CONTINUES AS FAMILY MEMBERS HOLD EMERGENCY MEETING 
[LOC JOHANNESBURG] - Singing crowds gathered outside the hospital where [PER Nelson Mandela] , [LOC South Africa’s] former president , lay in a critical state for a third consecutive day Tuesday , as family members held an emergency meeting at his ancestral village . 
Mandela’s eldest daughter , [PER Makaziwe] , at least two grandchildren and clan elders gathered at Mandela’s retirement house in [LOC Qunu] , the remote southern village where he grew up , according to news media reports . 
The subject of the meeting was not publicly disclosed , but [PER Naplisi Mandela] , an elder of the [PER Mandela] family , told the [MISC South] [ORG African Press Association] that they had gathered to discuss “delicate matters” - a euphemism widely interpreted to mean preparations for [MISC Mandela’s] death . 
Meanwhile , in [LOC Pretoria] , doctors continued to treat [PER Mandela] for a lung ailment that he contracted on [LOC Robben Island] , the notorious apartheid-era prison where he spent much of his 27 years behind bars until his release in 1990 . 
He was hospitalized June 8 , his fourth hospitalization since late last year . 
In a statement , President [PER Jacob Zuma] said [ORG Mandela’s] condition was unchanged . 
On Sunday , he visited [PER Mandela] and pronounced that his state had deteriorated from stable to critical . 
Noting that [PER Mandela’s] 95th birthday is on July 18 , [PER Zuma] urged [MISC South Africans] to celebrate his achievements . 
Still , after 18 days of anxious vigil , many appeared to be steeling themselves for the worst . 
Larger-than-usual crowds gathered at the gates of the [LOC Mediclinic Heart Hospital] to pay tribute to [PER Mandela] , as people dropped off cards at a growing shrine and sang songs . 
“There is no one like you , [PER Nelson Mandela] , ” one group sang in the [MISC Sotho] language . 
The emotional scenes were part of a perceptible shift in the national mood . 
Until recently , many [MISC South Africans] had avoided talking about [MISC Mandela’s] fate , calling it culturally inappropriate to speculate about any ailing figure , much less one as revered as [PER Mandela] , who played a central role in [MISC South Africa’s] transition from white-led minority rule to historic multirace elections in 1994 . 
But now many are openly talking about the prospect of bidding him farewell . 
Mandela’s declining condition came as President [PER Barack Obama] prepared to arrive in [LOC South Africa] on Friday on the second leg of an [MISC African] tour that will also take him to [LOC Tanzania] and [LOC Senegal] . 
But the [MISC South African] government said a planned meeting between [LOC Obama] and [LOC Mandela] - both the first black leaders of their countries - now looked unlikely . 
[MISC AFGHAN] COURT REVERSES CONVICTION IN TORTURE OF YOUNG WOMAN 
[LOC KABUL] , [LOC Afghanistan] - A court has reversed the convictions of three [MISC Afghans] jailed for torturing a young relative who had refused to become a prostitute , alarming activists who had celebrated the guilty verdicts as a warning to all those who would seek to reverse the strides made by women here in the past 12 years . 
A family had bought the young woman , [PER Sahar Gul] , from her stepbrother for $5,000 and had forced her to marry in 2011 , when she was just 13 or 14 . 
When she refused to consummate the marriage , her in-laws locked her in a basement , where they burned her with hot wires , pulled out her fingernails and twisted her skin with pliers for months . 
She was discovered in December 2011 curled up in a dank and dark corner of the cellar and badly malnourished . 
[PER Gul] now lives in a shelter in [LOC Kabul] . 
Her case attracted widespread attention in [LOC Afghanistan] and abroad . 
Three of her in-laws were convicted last year of attempted murder , and each was sentenced to 10 years in prison . 
The convictions were upheld on appeal , although her husband , who is in his 30s , remains at large . 
Last month , however , in a decision that received little publicity , the [ORG Supreme Court] sent the case back to the appeals court , saying that the violence appeared to warrant convictions for assault , not attempted murder , according to lawyers for the defendants . 
The appeals court agreed , voiding the convictions and ordering that the defendants - Gul’s mother-in-law , sister-in-law and father-in-law - be set free . 
The two women were released this week after about a year in prison , the lawyers said . 
They were not sure whether the father-in-law was yet out of prison . 
As word spread in [LOC Kabul] on Wednesday , [MISC Western] officials said they were still gathering details but would probably have a response in the coming days . 
[MISC Afghan] women’s rights activists reacted with alarm and said they would press to have the three defendants retried . 
“There’s smoke coming out of my hair . 
I am so angry , ” said [PER Manizha Naderi] , the executive director of Women for [MISC Afghan] Women . 
“This poor girl was in the basement for months . 
If she wasn’t rescued , she would be dead . 
She was starved and burned and had her fingernails pulled out . 
How is this not attempted murder ? ” 
The courts’ decisions make “a statement that violence against women is not that important , that [LOC Afghanistan] is becoming more conservative , ” [PER Naderi] added . 
[PER MICHAEL MASTROMARINO] , DENTIST GUILTY IN ORGAN SCHEME , DIES AT 49 
[PER Michael Mastromarino] , a former dental surgeon who became a tabloid sensation when he was charged with running a $4.6 million enterprise that plundered tissue and bone from corpses at funeral homes and sold them for transplants and research , died on Sunday at [LOC St.] [LOC Luke’s Cornwall Hospital] in [LOC Newburgh] , [LOC N.Y.] He was 49 and still serving a prison term . 
The cause was complications of metastatic liver cancer , [PER Mario Gallucci] , Mastromarino’s lawyer , said . 
The technology that allows the transplantation of critical organs also enables the far more common transplantation of tissue: bone can be used to repair fractures , veins for heart bypass surgery , and tendons and ligaments can restore mobility . 
Harvesting organs is allowed in [LOC New York] state , provided the donor does not carry a potentially communicable disease , the survivors approve and the person is not too old . 
But there are nowhere near enough willing donors to meet the demand for tissue , so the profit from one body can reach six figures . 
Mastromarino became licensed by [LOC New York] state to supply tissue banks and manufacturers of biological surgical instruments after his dental license was suspended in 2002 because of a drug addiction . 
He established a network of undertakers , whom he paid up to $1,000 per corpse , and soon took on assistants and formed a business based in [LOC New Jersey] , [ORG Biomedical Tissue Services] . 
He reportedly made $10,000 to $15,000 per body . 
But Mastromarino harvested organs and tissue from bodies without consent from the survivors , the authorities said , and removed material from people with cancer , [MISC HIV] and other diseases . 
He then forged paperwork , including consent forms and death certificates , to make the cause of death and age acceptable . 
The police began investigating irregularities at the [PER Daniel George] & [LOC Son Funeral Home] in [LOC Bensonhurst] , [LOC Brooklyn] , in 2005 . 
News reports included lurid details , like what the police called a secret room in the funeral home equipped with specialized surgical equipment ; leg bones replaced by PVC pipe so bodies would appear intact at viewings ( this procedure is common in lawful bone removal ) ; and the fact that one of the victims was [PER Alistair Cooke] , the [MISC British] journalist and former host of “Masterpiece Theater , ” whose arm and leg bones were taken even though he had had cancer . 
Mastromarino was charged in 2006 , along with two of his workers and an embalmer . 
He pleaded guilty in 2008 to numerous charges of enterprise corruption , reckless endangerment and body stealing and was sentenced to 15 to 30 years in prison . 
He and his wife , [PER Barbara] , agreed to pay $4.6 million to the district attorney’s office , to be distributed among the victims’ relatives . 
[PER Michael Mastromarino] was born in [LOC Brooklyn] on Sept. 16 , 1963 . 
He graduated from the [ORG University of Pittsburgh] and the [ORG New York] [LOC University College of Dentistry] . 
Mastromarino had surgical offices in [LOC New Jersey] and [LOC Manhattan] . 
He was a co-author , with [PER Michael R. Wiland] , of the book “Smile: [ORG How Dental Implants Can Transform Your Life.”] 
[PER Mastromarino] , who was divorced , is survived by two sons , [PER Michael] and [PER Jerry] . 
As for [PER Cooke] , his daughter , [PER Susan Cooke Kittredge] , said in an article in [LOC New York] magazine that “he would have been just horrified” by the illegal harvesting . 
But , she said , “at the same time , he would have appreciated the [MISC Dickensian] nature of it.” 
EXTRADITED COLOMBIAN TO FACE CHARGES OF DRUG TRAFFICKING 
A [MISC Colombian] who has been described by his country’s president as “the last of the great kingpins” was extradited to the [LOC United States] from [LOC Colombia] on Tuesday to face charges that he manufactured large quantities of cocaine that he then trafficked to the [LOC U.S.] and elsewhere . 
[PER Daniel Barrera] is to be arraigned Wednesday and Thursday in [LOC U.S.] district courts in [LOC Manhattan] and [LOC Brooklyn] , where he faces separate indictments . 
After those prosecutions , he will be arraigned in [LOC Miami] on additional charges , the authorities said . 
[PER Barrera] , also known as [PER El Loco] , was arrested in September in [LOC Venezuela] as a result of a complex operation that included [MISC Colombian] and [MISC Venezuelan] authorities , the [ORG CIA] , the [ORG Drug Enforcement Administration] and the [MISC British] intelligence . 
He was later sent to [LOC Colombia] , and his extradition was announced by the [LOC U.S.] attorneys in the three jurisdictions and other officials , including [PER Raymond W. Kelly] , the police commissioner of [LOC New York] ; and [PER Michele M. Leonhart] , the head of the [ORG DEA] . 
An indictment in [LOC Manhattan] says that [PER Barrera] relied on two [MISC Colombian] terrorist organizations to carry out his operations , buying raw cocaine paste from members of the [ORG Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia] , or [ORG FARC] , and processing it in laboratories in areas controlled by another group , to which he paid fees . 
Barrera’s organization produced upward of 400 tons of cocaine a year , “enriching itself and the two terrorist organizations it paid off , ” said [PER Preet Bharara] , the [LOC U.S.] attorney in [LOC Manhattan] . 
[PER Loretta E. Lynch] , the [LOC U.S.] attorney in [LOC Brooklyn] , said Barrera’s organization was “marked by its worldwide reach , ruthless criminality and staggering profits.” 
[PER Barrera] is charged in [LOC Manhattan] with one count of narcotics importation conspiracy , which carries a maximum sentence of life in prison . 
He faces a money laundering conspiracy charge in [LOC Brooklyn] . 
His lawyer declined to comment . 
Officials have said that [PER Barrera] , while residing in [LOC Venezuela] , changed his appearance through plastic surgery , slept in different places and burned his fingertips to try to make it impossible to identify him . 
