[PER Morsi] has not been seen publicly since his ouster July 3 . 
It is unclear where he is being held , or whether he and the others will face the charges in court . 
The ouster of [PER Morsi] and the subsequent suppression of the Brotherhood has enraged the group’s members and led to a spate of scapegoating attacks by [MISC Muslim] extremists against [MISC Christians] they accuse of supporting his fall , rights activists said . 
While tensions between the [MISC Christian] minority and extremist elements in the [MISC Muslim] majority are not new , attacks have been reported across the country - in the northern [ORG Sinai Peninsula] , in a resort town on the [ORG Mediterranean Coast] , in [LOC Port Said] along the [LOC Suez Canal] and in isolated villages in upper [LOC Egypt] . 
No special session , but protesters leave [LOC Capitol] 
[ORG Times/Herald Tallahassee Bureau] 
[LOC TALLAHASSEE] — They weren’t able to persuade Gov. [PER Rick Scott] to call a special session on the controversial ' 's tand your ground’' law . 
But the student activists known as the [ORG Dream Defenders] drew national attention to their cause by holding the longest sit-in demonstration at the [LOC Florida Capitol] in recent memory . 
On Thursday , the [MISC Miami-based] group announced that their record-setting protest is over — for now , at least . 
" After 31 days and 30 nights , we are leaving the [LOC Capitol] for our next phase , " [ORG Dream Defenders] executive director [PER Phillip Agnew] said . 
[PER Agnew] said the group would register thousands of new voters in the coming months and return to the Capitol for legislative committee hearings in the fall . 
The [ORG Dream Defenders’] occupation of the [LOC Capitol] began July 16 , three days after [PER George Zimmerman] was acquitted in the shooting death of [PER Trayvon Martin] , an unarmed teenager from [LOC Miami-Dade] . 
They promised to stay until [PER Scott] convened a special session on ' 's tand your ground’' and several other criminal justice issues . 
" We said if ( [PER Scott] ) would not give us a seat at the table , we would sleep on the floor until ( he ) gave us what we deserved , " [PER Agnew] said . 
[PER Scott] met with the protesters July 18 but refused their demands . 
The [ORG Dream Defenders] tried to persuade state lawmakers to call the session themselves , but they couldn’t muster the 96 votes needed . 
As of Thursday , 42 lawmakers had voted in favor of holding the session , 90 voted against , and 28 had yet to vote . 
This week , House Speaker [PER Will Weatherford] called for the group’s departure . 
The [ORG Dream Defenders] claimed several victories , including a promise from [LOC Weatherford] to hold a hearing on the ' 's tand your ground’' law this fall . 
The group also secured meetings with the [ORG Florida Department of Law Enforcement] to discuss racial profiling , [PER Agnew] said , and began a dialogue with the [ORG state Department of Juvenile Justice] on the disproportionate number of young [MISC African-American] men in prison . 
[PER Agnew] said the [ORG Dream Defenders] had not been pressured to wrap up their protest by the governor’s office or state law enforcement officials . 
The [ORG Capitol Police] who had watched over the group , [PER Agnew] added , ' 'd eserved a raise . " 
The state spent a total of $153,630 on police overtime throughout the protest , according to [ORG FDLE] . 
The [ORG Dream Defenders] didn’t anticipate their stay would last a month or that singer [PER Harry Belafonte] , rapper [PER Talib Kweli] or civil rights leaders [PER Jesse Jackson] and [PER Julian Bond] would join them in the [LOC Capitol] . 
" Gov. [PER Scott] , through his inaction , created a new group of leaders who will have a lasting effect on [LOC Florida] , " said state Rep. [PER Alan Williams] , a [LOC Tallahassee] [MISC Democrat] who mentored the group . 
When they packed up their belongings and left the [LOC Capitol] Thursday evening , the young activists wondered aloud if there had been some level of divine intervention along the way . 
On Wednesday , the state [ORG Department of Management Services] announced plans to test the fire alarm system in the [LOC Capitol] . 
The testing would last from 8 p.m. until midnight , and involve an " incredibly loud , high-pitch noise , " according to a press release . 
But before the testing began , the building adjacent to the [LOC Capitol] was struck by lightning . 
The [ORG Department of Management Services] decided to perform maintenance on that building’s fire alarm system instead . 
" I don’t know how to explain it , " [ORG Dream Defender] [PER Steven Pargett] said . 
" Some things are just meant to happen . " 
Times/Herald staff writers [PER Tia Mitchell] and [PER Michael Van Sickler] contributed to this report . 
A PINK-SLIP THANKS FOR A MAJOR DECISION 
On Baseball ) ; 
When [PER John Gaherin] , the chief labor negotiator for [MISC Major League Baseball] , arrived for a meeting with the chief of the players union and baseball’s arbitrator , he carried an envelope in the pocket of his suit jacket . 
It was two days before Christmas 1975 , not a time to be conducting serious business , but [PER Gaherin] and [PER Marvin Miller] , the executive director of the union , knew why [PER Peter Seitz] , the arbitrator , had summoned them . 
They knew that the subject of the meeting would be as serious a bit of business as baseball had ever experienced , and [PER Gaherin] went to the meeting prepared . 
[PER Seitz] had informally telegraphed his decision in a grievance case , and now he would formally hand his written opinion to the two men . 
As soon as he did , [PER Gaherin] handed [PER Seitz] the envelope . 
“You’re fired , ” it said in effect . 
Such is the perilous life of impartial arbitrators in baseball and other professional sports . 
Either side - the league or the union - has the right to fire them . 
Like managers , they are hired to be fired . 
“He told me he had expected as much , ” [PER Michael Seitz] , Peter’s son , said in a recent telephone interview . 
“His feeling was there was no other way to decide the case , because the baseball owners had been stupid in assuming that when they didn’t have a player under contract , they still had a contractual hold on him.” 
[PER Fredric R. Horowitz] , a 64-year-old lawyer from [LOC Santa Monica] , [LOC Calif.] , is the latest to take a turn . 
He will arbitrate [PER Alex Rodriguez’s] appeal of his 211-game suspension . 
While arbitrators pay for their decisions , which anger either the owners or the players , they don’t always receive credit for the significance of their decisions . 
[PER Seitz] , for example , was responsible for creating free agency in baseball with his decision in the 1975 [PER Andy Messersmith-Dave McNally] grievance , but I believe , as [PER Marvin Miller] used to complain , that some reports in the news media , including in [ORG The New York Times] , mistakenly credited other cases: [PER Curt Flood’s] 1970 lawsuit against baseball and [PER Catfish Hunter’s] 1974 grievance against [PER Charlie Finley] . 
Flood’s suit challenged the game’s reserve clause , the rule that bound a player to his team until he was traded , sold or released . 
Hunter’s grievance contended that [PER Finley] , the [LOC Oakland] [MISC Athletics’] owner , had breached his contract . 
The Hunter case was exactly what the union argued , a breach-of-contract case . 
[PER Finley] had not paid the premium on Hunter’s annuity , as stipulated in his contract , [PER Richard Moss] , the union lawyer , said , and the pitcher should be a free agent as a result . 
[PER Seitz] , in his first year as baseball’s arbitrator , agreed with [MISC Moss’] argument and declared Hunter a free agent . 
A year later , when [PER Seitz] ruled in the [MISC Messersmith-McNally] grievance , he did not cite the Hunter decision as a basis for this decision . 
As a breach-of-contract case , it affected no player but Hunter . 
No other player could gain free agency based on Seitz’s decision on Hunter . 
“It didn’t change the mind of a single owner , ” [PER Miller] said of the Hunter decision in one of the many conversations we had on the subject . 
" The owners’ position on free agency was the same after the Hunter case as it was before . " 
Nor , [PER Miller] added , did the [PER Flood] case affect the owners’ thinking on the reserve clause and free agency . 
The reserve clause had forever been the tie that bound players to their teams , whether they liked it or not . 
[PER Flood] did not like it , and when the [ORG St. Louis Cardinals] traded him to [LOC Philadelphia] , he opted to sue the commissioner rather than go to the [ORG Phillies] , contending that he should have the right to play where he wanted . 
The suit went all the way to the [ORG U.S. Supreme Court] , where [PER Flood] lost . 
The owners always argued that elimination of the reserve clause would ruin baseball , [PER Miller] said , and Flood’s loss in the lawsuit emboldened them to maintain their position . 
As heroic as [PER Flood] was in pursuing his lawsuit , it fell well short of having an effect . 
Its failure was one of the reasons the owners were so confident of winning the [MISC Messersmith-McNally] grievance in court when they appealed [ORG Seitz’s] decision , which said players could be free agents if they played the renewal year in their contract without signing a new contract . 
What the owners failed to understand , in their inexperience in labor matters , was that judges rarely overruled an arbitrator’s decision , doing so only if an arbitrator’s authority had been exceeded . 
The clubs and the commissioner have not done particularly well before arbitrators in instances where players have been suspended for conduct off the field . 
That history continued last year when [PER Shyam Das] overturned [PER Ryan Braun’s] 50-game suspension . 
[PER Das] was fired after his [PER Braun] ruling . 
Baseball would have preferred settling all of the doping cases stemming from the investigation into [PER Biogenesis] , an anti-aging clinic that is believed to have distributed banned substances to baseball players . 
The union also seemed eager to settle . 
But [PER Rodriguez] has appealed his 211-game suspension . 
Given the volatility of the [PER Rodriguez] case , it would not be surprising if Horowitz’s first major case were his last . 
FORMER JPMORGAN EMPLOYEE SURRENDERS IN 'LONDON WHALE' CASE 
Weeks after the [LOC U.S.] government charged [PER Javier Martin-Artajo] , a former [ORG JPMorgan Chase] employee , with hiding trading losses that ultimately reached more than $6 billion , he had his first day in court Tuesday as he surrendered to [MISC Spanish] authorities and kicked off what could be a lengthy extradition process . 
Martin-Artajo , a [MISC Spaniard] who worked in the bank’s [LOC London] office , was released soon after his surrender and arrest . 
He agreed to remain at the disposal of the [MISC Spanish] judiciary , but it was unclear whether his passport was confiscated to prevent him from leaving the country , according to a person briefed on the matter . 
The criminal charges stem from a risky bet at [LOC JPMorgan’s] chief investment office in [LOC London] , where [PER Martin-Artajo] worked . 
The bet involved so-called credit derivatives , which allow traders to bet on the perceived health of companies like [ORG American Airlines] . 
When the bet soured in the spring of 2012 , prosecutors claim , [PER Martin-Artajo] and [PER Julien Grout] , a lower-ranking employee , deliberately overstated the value of their positions to hide hundreds of millions of dollars in losses . 
The two were charged with wire fraud , falsifying bank records and contributing to false regulatory filings . 
Prosecutors also charged them with conspiracy to commit those crimes . 
The arrest in [LOC Spain] , the latest development in an episode that left a rare stain on [MISC JPMorgan’s] once-stellar reputation , underscores the challenge [LOC U.S.] authorities face in their pursuit of the traders . 
After announcing charges this month against [PER Martin-Artajo] and [PER Grout] , federal prosecutors and the [ORG FBI] in [LOC Manhattan] have encountered logistical hurdles . 
[MISC British] police issued an arrest warrant for [PER Martin-Artajo] at the behest of authorities in [LOC New York] , and then visited his house in [LOC London] only to find that he was gone . 
According to his lawyers , [PER Martin-Artajo] left [LOC London] “on a long-planned vacation” to his native [LOC Spain] without knowing of the pending charges . 
[PER Grout] , for his part , left [LOC London] this year for his native [LOC France] , which typically does not extradite its citizens . 
His lawyer , [PER Edward Little] , explained that his client also spent a brief period in the [LOC U.S.] , where his wife’s family lives . 
According to a person close to the case , both of the former traders have indicated through their lawyers that they are open to extradition but only if prosecutors recommend bail . 
Prosecutors have not charged a third trader , nicknamed “the [LOC London] [PER Whale.”] 
That trader , [PER Bruno Iksil] , has reached a deal with the authorities in [LOC Manhattan] that will spare him charges as long as he cooperates against his two former colleagues . 
LEADER OF FAR-RIGHT PARTY IN [LOC GREECE] IS JAILED 
[LOC ATHENS] , [LOC Greece] - The leader of the extreme-right [ORG Golden Dawn] party was returned to custody Thursday after appearing before a [MISC Greek] magistrate on charges of setting up a criminal organization , part of the government’s crackdown on a party described by [MISC Greek] and [MISC European] authorities as neo-Nazi and violent . 
The magistrate’s order to remand [PER Nikos Michaloliakos] , the first political party leader to face jail since Greece’s seven-year military dictatorship ended in 1974 , came a day after three of his fellow lawmakers facing similar charges were released from custody and told not to leave the country , and a fourth was ordered held pending trial . 
During more than six hours of testimony in an [LOC Athens] courtroom , [PER Michaloliakos] condemned the murder last month of a 34-year-old hip-hop artist and anti-fascist , [PER Pavlos Fyssas] , by a self-professed supporter of [ORG Golden Dawn] , and said he did not know whether members of the party were involved in violence , according to a court official . 
“I condemn the murder , like I condemn violence in general , ” he was quoted as saying . 
“I am not a [MISC Nazi.”] 
Leaving court early Thursday , [PER Michaloliakos] was defiant . 
“Long live [ORG Golden Dawn] ! 
Victory ! ” he declared as his wife , [PER Eleni Zaroulia] , another [MISC Golden Dawn] member of Parliament , cried , “You’re a diamond ! ” and his daughter , [PER Ourania Michaloliakou] , urged him , “Don’t buckle , don’t give in ! ” 
[PER Michaloliakos] was transferred to the capital’s high-security [LOC Korydallos] prison later in the day along with [PER Yiannis Lagos] , another [ORG Golden Dawn] lawmaker . 
[PER Giorgos Patelis] , the head of the party’s chapter in [LOC Nikaia] , near the spot where [PER Fyssas] was fatally stabbed , and an officer from the regional police precinct accused of supplying [MISC Golden Dawn] with information were taken to two other jails in central [LOC Greece] , state television reported . 
According to the police , [LOC Lagos] telephoned [PER Michaloliakos] half an hour after the killing of [PER Fyssas] on Sept. 18 . 
The lawmaker has been tied to protection and prostitution rackets as well as blackmail and money laundering , according to secret service documents leaked to the [MISC Greek] media this week . 
Later Thursday , a sixth lawmaker , [PER Christos Pappas] , the party’s second in command , was also ordered returned to custody after testifying for at least six hours before a magistrate . 
He was to stay overnight at the [LOC Athens] police headquarters before his transfer to prison . 
Arriving at the capital’s court complex , [PER Pappas] told reporters , “Golden [PER Dawn] will run in the next elections , whenever they may be.” 
PROTESTS [LOC AS CITY] COLLEGE CLOSES A STUDENT CENTER 
[PER Julie Turkewitz] contributed reporting . 
[LOC NEW YORK] - It was just a small room , one of hundreds in [LOC City] [MISC College’s] [LOC North Academic Center] , but over the years the [PER Guillermo Morales/Assata Shakur] Student and [ORG Community Center] had taken on a significance beyond its square footage . 
To student organizers who used it as their meeting space , it was a place for lesbian and gay activists , women’s rights groups , community organizations and others to make common cause . 
To outside critics it was a symbol of campus politics gone berserk , its unofficial name a glorification of [ORG City College] alumni who had joined revolutionary organizations and gone on the lam . 
But officials at [ORG City College] , part of [LOC the] [ORG City University of New York] , insisted that charged history was not a factor when they decided that the room would be better used as an annex for the school’s career services office , two floors below . 
Without notice , security officers entered the room this past weekend , boxed up and removed its contents - and just to be on the safe side , locked down the entire building , including the library . 
With just a day to go before midterm exams , the library was reopened after a few hours . 
But Room 3/201 was not , resulting at least for a brief while in the incongruous sight of closed doors emblazoned with a bold , black fist , below a crisp white sign that read Careers and Professional Development . 
( The door had been repainted , without the fist , as of Monday afternoon . ) 
Given the center’s history , it could not have come entirely as a surprise when its former occupants let their dissatisfaction be known . 
They organized protest rallies , distributed fliers , posted videos and demanded [LOC that] [ORG City College] be shut down . 
A protester was arrested . 
And just in time for an outdoor demonstration on Monday , someone set off a fire alarm , sending hundreds of people out onto the plaza . 
“I think that the [ORG CUNY] administration is really scared of a lot of the organizing and community-building coming out of the building , ” said [PER Alyssia Osorio] , director of the [ORG Morales/Shakur Center] . 
“We provide so many services for the community - know-your-rights training , a farm share that provides healthy food , we’ve run a soup kitchen , we have provided baby-sitting services for people in the community.” 
[PER Deidra Hill] , vice president of communications at [ORG City College] , called the administration’s takeover of the room a matter of space . 
She said the career services office needed a quiet area where students can “meet with outside employers , with alumni , to seek advice on careers.” 
[ORG City College] said the unusually swift action was necessary . 
“We were concerned that we might have to move people , and that would not have been safe , ” [PER Hill] said . 
As for the protests , “Students were exercising their free speech rights , which the college supports , ” she said . 
[LOC The] [ORG City College] students whom the center’s name honors have never visited . 
[PER Guillermo Morales] , a leader of the [LOC FALN] , a [MISC Puerto Rican] independence group that claimed responsibility for a deadly bombing in [LOC New York] , fled to [LOC Cuba] . 
So did [PER Shakur] , who as a member of the [ORG Black Liberation Army] was convicted in the 1973 killing of a [LOC New Jersey] State trooper . 
In 2006 , a student objected to the name of the center . 
In the ensuing controversy , CUNY’s chancellor ordered that it be changed . 
But it stuck . 
[PER Taf Sourov] , 19 , a member of the [ORG Revolutionary Student Coordinating Committee] , a group that regularly met there , said he believed the closing was retaliation for student protests against [PER David H. Petraeus] , the former [ORG CIA] director and military commander , who is teaching a course at the [LOC Macaulay Honors College] . 
“I practically lived out of the room , ” [PER Sourov] said . 
“I would do my homework in there . 
I did my political work in there . 
I would socialize in there . 
I feel like part of me is ripped out.” 
[PER Dewhurst] wants to bill feds for undocumented prisoners 
[LOC AUSTIN] , [LOC Texas] -- Days after calling for the impeachment of President [PER Barack Obama] , Lt. Gov. [PER David Dewhurst] is demanding that the president pay for the 130,000 undocumented immigrants who are housed in county jails across [LOC Texas] -- a tab that could run nearly $157 million in the past two years alone . 
In a letter to [LOC Obama] , [PER Dewhurst] said the federal government should reimburse [LOC Texas] counties for the cost of housing the undocumented immigrants because the feds have failed to secure the [LOC U.S.] [LOC Mexico] border as they should have . 
" [MISC It’s] time we ask for that money back , " [PER Dewhurst] said in an email to supporters this week , asking them to sign a petition supporting his position . 
" It’s outrageous that county jails pay for housing to more than 130,000 people that illegally enter our state . 
" In my experience , I believe the immigration conversation begins and ends with strict border security , as our counties can no longer fund this massive financial burden . " 
In his letter to [LOC Obama] , [LOC Dewhurst] wrote: " The dollars expended in this fashion would be better spent enhancing law enforcement efforts to better protect our citizens . " 
No word yet from [LOC Washington] on what they think of Dewhurst’s demand , but don’t expect a check to be arriving anytime soon . 
[PER Dewhurst] , who has drawn three [MISC GOP] challengers in his re-election bid , has made a sharp turn to the right in his political rhetoric since losing a [LOC U.S.] [ORG Senate] runoff to tea party star [PER Ted Cruz] in July 2012 . 
Two weeks ago , [PER Dewhurst] publicly advocated [MISC Obama’s] impeachment at a tea party forum in [LOC Fort Worth] -- a move that drew surprise since it came from [ORG Texas’ No.] 2 officeholder . 
State and county officials have complained for years that detained immigrants are costing local taxpayers , and federal officials have declined to reimburse any costs because the jailed suspects are being held on local charges . 
Similarly , state officials have also complained that state prisons are holding thousands of undocumented immigrants who were convicted of state crimes . 
At one point last year , well over 12,000 state convicts had deportation detainers on them -- meaning that as soon as they complete their sentence or are paroled they are subject to being deported , officials said . 
Most are [MISC Mexican] citizens , prison officials said . 
Proposals to deport convicts serving time for nonviolent crimes before they were paroled have failed to gain support from legislative leaders , who feared if they were paroled and returned home they would simply slip back across the border into [LOC Texas] . 
The savings from that plan were estimated to be at least $15 million , officials said at the time . 
[PER Mike Ward] writes for the [ORG Austin American-Statesman] . 
E-mail: mward ( at ) statesman.com . 
